---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="Daycare Business Plan | Childcare Business Plan"
    description="Your daycare business plan needs accurate financial projections based on your state's regulations and local market conditions."
>
    <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16 px-4">
        <!-- 1. OWNERSHIP FRAMING -->
        <section class="text-center mb-16">
            <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
                YOUR Daycare Business Plan
            </h1>
            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
                A daycare business plan is only as good as the numbers behind
                it. Generic templates can't account for your state's regulatory
                environment, your local market rates, or your specific business
                model.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- 2. FACTORS THAT AFFECT OUTCOME -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
                What Affects Your Projections
            </h2>
            <div class="prose prose-lg text-gray-600">
                <p class="mb-4">
                    Financial projections are the heart of any business plan,
                    but daycare financials are unusually dependent on
                    location-specific factors. Your state determines your
                    maximum capacity, which caps your revenue potential. Your
                    local market determines what rates parents will pay, which
                    drives your income per child. Your licensing tier determines
                    your staffing requirements, which affects your largest
                    operating expense.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-4">
                    Startup costs vary just as dramatically. A home daycare
                    might require minimal renovations or extensive modifications
                    depending on local health and safety codes. A center-based
                    program faces completely different equipment, facility, and
                    compliance costs that vary by state and municipality.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Beyond hard costs, your business plan needs to account for
                    realistic enrollment curves, seasonal attendance patterns,
                    and the competitive landscape in your area. None of these
                    factors can be accurately estimated using national averages
                    or generic templates.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 3. WHY GENERIC ADVICE FAILS -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
                Why Online Advice Often Conflicts
            </h2>
            <div class="prose prose-lg text-gray-600">
                <p class="mb-4">
                    Download a daycare business plan template and you'll find
                    placeholder numbers that might be completely wrong for your
                    situation. Fill-in-the-blank financial projections can't
                    account for the specific regulatory constraints and market
                    conditions that will define your actual business
                    performance.
                </p>
                <p class="mb-4">
                    Investors, lenders, and partners don't want to see
                    hypothetical numbers—they want to see projections grounded
                    in your specific opportunity. That means starting with
                    accurate data about what's actually possible in your state,
                    with your license type, in your market.
                </p>
                <p>
                    A business plan built on generic assumptions won't just be
                    less useful—it could lead to catastrophic planning errors.
                    Overestimating income or underestimating costs by even small
                    percentages can mean the difference between viability and
                    failure.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- 4. CTA TO CALCULATOR -->
        <section class="text-center py-12 px-8 glass-panel rounded-3xl">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
                See How Much YOU Could Make in Your State
            </h2>
            <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">
                Start your business plan with accurate income projections based
                on your state's regulations.
            </p>
            <a
                href="/tools/income-builder"
                class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-teal-600 hover:bg-teal-700 text-white font-medium px-8 py-4 shadow-lg transition-all"
            >
                Use the Free Calculator →
            </a>
        </section>
    </main>
</Layout>
